@node Introduction "Introduction"

 GERMAN is the second LGUI Language disk to be released. The first LGUI
 Language disk is TAGALOG (National Language Of The Philippines).

 The GERMAN Files were created as follows:

  As I cannot think of 1000+ Sentences off the top of my head, of course I
  had to look at Books for Ideas. After reading various Books, etc I chose
  the Sentences and Words I would like to Use - Not Copy.

  From there I filtered out Long Sentences, Words that I thought might be
  too long to remember (when used with a long sentence for example), etc.
  Using my chosen Filtered Out Sentences and Words I changed some of the
  Nouns and Adjectives so to give better, more useful, sentences. I then
  created the GERMAN Files.

  To make sure the German Files were as correct as I could make them I cross
  referenced (Not Copied) the Words and Sentences with various Books, Audio
  Tapes, etc. So you should find most, if not all, words and sentences are
  the common way of writing/saying those words and sentences.

  Obviously, some things in the Books, etc I read are going to be exactly
  the same as in the German Files simply because if that is the way things
  are said (regardless of Books, Writing, etc) then that is the way things
  are said.

 @{" File Notes " Link "Notes"}
@{fg shine}
 Warning@{fg text}

 I Do NOT Say, Suggest, etc that the LGUI GERMAN Files are Correct, etc
 in any Way, Shape or Form. If you decide to use the LGUI GERMAN Files
 you do so knowing the above.
@endnode

@node Notes "File Notes"

 Throughout the GERMAN Files I have tried to make the Sentences as easy as
 possible to learn, but at the same time make them Easy-Medium, Short-Long,
 etc thus hopefully getting the learning balance right. The sentences have
 also been Mixed-Up. For example. If you had a question sentence like
 "What is your Job?" and an answer sentence like "I am a Teacher". This may
 seem fine - You would simply remember the `I am a Teacher' sentence when
 someone asked you "What is your Job?" because it was in sequence (Question
 followed by Answer). However, this sequence remembering pattern would be no
 good if you wanted to use another reply like "I do not have a Job". Simply
 because your brain would more than likely bring up the `I am a Teacher'
 sentence before remembering it has other replies it could use, like
 `I do not have a Job'.

 The Sentences I have put into the GERMAN Files, together with the
 Categories, have been designed for purposes such as:

 * People who wish to learn GERMAN over a One Year period for example.

 * People who wish to learn GERMAN as a Language, as opposed to just a
   Tourist Language, etc.
 
 * People who need to learn the Basics of GERMAN - Perhaps because they
   have a German Partner, A Job in Germany, etc.
@{fg fill}
 I have tried to put the `Most Common' Question, Answer, etc Sentences into
 the GERMAN Files. However, you must realize that the current sentences
 are mainly Question, Answer, Comment and Command type sentences. By this I
 mean - It is very possible to make a Conversation from the sentences, but
 my main aim was to allow you to be able to Ask Questions, Say Comments,
 Issue Commands, etc (on an Easy Level?) whilst on Holiday, when talking to
 Filipinos, etc.

 I have made the German files so that you work your way Left-Downwards on
 the LGUI Options Menu before going Right-Downwards. This is so you can see
 the easy? Sentences first before progressing onto not so easy Sentences.
 I would say that if you can learn the `Answering the Telephone' category
 and the `Talking To/Meeting People' category then you should be Ok.
@{fg text}
 Throughout the GERMAN Files I have inserted the following symbols:

      [Word/s]  -  Square Brackets mean the Word/s can be changed, for one
                   of the same type for example.

                   If a Word is a NOUN for example then you could change it
                   for a different NOUN. This might also change that
                   Sentence's meaning or just the Word itself.

      {Word/s}  -  Braces mean the Word/s in the Braces, when added to a
                   Sentence, may extend that sentence and/or change that
                   sentence's meaning.


      {....}    -  This means you you could continue the Sentence.
                   For example:

                   What Do You Think {....}

                   What Do You Think {About TOM}, {Of This Dress}, etc.


      (Word/s)  -  Brackets mean My own comment/s about a Word and/or
                   Sentence.


 Item1 / Item2  -  This means Words and/or Sentences are seperated, perhaps
                   because Item2 is showing you that it can be said
                   differently to Item1 but still have the same meaning as
                   Item1.


   Item1/Item2  -  This means a Word and/or Sentence may have two different
                   meanings when Translated to Item1 and Item2. Or may have
                   the same meaning when Translated to Item1 and Item2 but
                   have different ways/words to show the meaning.


        Blox/y  -  Blox or Bloxy are used as a Surname.


      H.S-Shop  -  H.S Shop is used to denote an High Street Shop. The
                   reason for Blox/y and H.S Shop is just to protect myself.
                   I did not want to use a proper name of a person or shop
                   just in case I got complaints.

 These symbols are in most, if not all, Categories to Help you. However, I
 have left some Words/Sentences without symbols so that you can test your-
 self. There are also a variety of ways to say certain sentences/things
 which could also be helpful for testing purposes.

 PLEASE NOTE: THE SYMBOLS ABOVE ARE FOR READABILITY PURPOSES ONLY. THEY ARE
              NOTHING TO DO WITH LGUI WHATSOEVER.

 The last Miscellaneous/Various Category is not really Mixed, as in the true
 sense of the word Miscellaneous. By this I mean, the last category has got
 a mixture of the other categories in it aswell. For example, instead of
 putting every `Home' sentence into the Home Category I just put the every
 day `Home' sentences into that category and then put the Not-Used-Every-Day
 'Home' sentences into the last Miscellaneous Category. Thus, at a later
 learning stage you could add Miscellaneous `Home' sentences to the Home
 Category.

 Finally, You will notice that I use the same words over and over again in
 the Sentences. This is because I believe that by doing this you have a
 better chance of remembering the sentence structures. For example:

      Sie Ist [Schön] - She Is Beautiful

 Sie Ist Sehr [Schön] - She Is Very Beatiful

 All you had to remember was the SEHR part of the sentence, when the
 sentence changed. If I had repeated the SIE IST [SCHÖN] sentence 10 times
 for example, changing the SCHÖN word each time, this would of meant you
 having to remember 10 different words for the same sentence structure.

 @{" Grammar " Link "Grammar"}
@endnode

@node Grammar "Grammar"

 This section, which describes some of the Basics of German Grammar, has
 been inserted for those who want to learn German as a Language (as opposed
 to a Tourist Language) rather than just remember sentences from the top of
 their heads for example.

 Grammar, to me, is a very long and complex subject - LGUI is not about
 teaching you Grammar. It is about showing you how Basic Words/Sentences of
 a language are Written and/or Spoken so that you can hopefully learn how to
 Write, Read and Speak those Basic Words/Sentences. Thus, if you want to
 find out more about German and its grammar it is upto you to do so - Hence
 the reason why this file only covers Basic Grammar/Notes.

@{fg shine} GENDER@{fg text}

 German has three Genders: Masculine, Feminine and Neuter. Gender simply
 defines how a sentence should be written/spoken. For example, if a word
 (Noun) is Masculine then you make the whole sentence (Adjectives, etc)
 masculine aswell (wherever possible). Masculine/Feminine has nothing to do
 with, you, the speaker - For example, do not think if you are a Man that
 you can only say Masculine sentences and that a Woman can only say Feminine
 sentences. This is not the case. Why gender in a language exists I do not
 know (I do not care if a `Door' is Masculine, Feminine, Butch or whatever!)

@{fg shine} CASES@{fg text}

 German also uses four Cases. Nominative (used for the Subject or Initiator
 of an Action or Speech), Accusative (used for the Person or Thing directly
 affected by the Action), Dative (used for the Recipient) and Genitive (used
 for the Possessor). These cases are used for Articles, Nouns, Pronouns and
 Adjectives according to their position. Do not worry too much about Case
 as most of the time LGUI Sentences use the Nominative Case (I.e. the simple
 ways to write THE, A, etc in a sentence).

 @{" Dictionary " Link "Dictionary"}


@{fg shine} NOUNS / ARTICLES@{fg text}

@{fg shine} The@{fg text}

 DER - Use when the Noun is Masculine. DER becomes DEM after the word
       ON (AUF), IN (IN), UNDER (UNTER), etc.

       THE Masculine: DER (Nominative), DEN (Accusative), DEM (Dative) and
                      DES (Genitive).

 DAS - Use when the Noun is Neuter. DAS becomes DEM after the word ON (AUF),
       IN (IN), UNDER (UNTER), etc.

       THE Neuter: DAS (Nominative), DAS (Accusative), DEM (Dative) and
                   DES (Genitive).

 DIE - Use when the Noun is Feminine. DIE becomes DER after the word ON
       (AUF), IN (IN), UNDER (UNTER), etc. DEN is used instead of DER when
       the noun is an Object or Accusative. Example:

       Have you got The KEY =  Haben Sie Den Schlüssel

       DAS and DER do not change in the Accusative case - it is only the
       Masculine Singular that changes:

       Have you an Aunt?  =  Haben Sie eine Tante?

       Who had the Book?  =  Wer hatte das Buch?

        We have the Cups  =  Wir haben die Tassen


       THE Feminine: DIE (Nominative), DIE (Accusative), DER (Dative)
                     and DER (Genitive).

@{fg shine} A@{fg text}

  EIN - Use when a word is Masculine. Einen Is used instead of EIN when the
        noun is an Object or Accusative. Example:

        He has A/An HAT  =  Er hat Einen Hut

        A Masculine: EIN (Nominative), EINEN (Accusative), EINEM (Dative)
                     and EINES (Genitive).

  EIN - Use when a word is Neuter.

        A Neuter: EIN (Nominative), EIN (Accusative), EINEM (Dative)
                  and EINES (Genitive).

 EINE - Use when a word is Feminine.

        A Feminine: EINE (Nominative), EINE (Accusative), EINER (Dative)
                    and EINER (Genitive).

 EIN becomes EINEM after the word ON (AUF), IN (IN), UNDER (UNTER), etc.
 Example:

 I live in a house  =  Ich wohne in einem haus

 EINE becomes EINER after the word ON (AUF), IN (IN), UNDER (UNTER), etc.
 Example:

 I live in a flat  =  Ich wohne in einer wohnung
@{fg fill}
 If the definite article (THE) is preceded by a Preposition (At, On, In, Of,
 etc) then the Preposition and the Definite Article can be/are combined as
 follows:

   AM  -  Combined from AN DEM (At The, On The, etc).

   IM  -  Combined from IN DEM (In The, Into The, etc).

  INS  -  Combined from IN DAS.

  UMS  -  Combined from UM DAS.

  VOM  -  Combined from VON DEM.

  ZUM  -  Masculine or Neuter. Combined from ZU DEM (For The, To The, etc).

  ZUR  -  Feminine. Combined from ZU DER (For The, To The, etc).

 AUFS  -  Combined from AUF DAS.

 BEIM  -  Combined from BEI DEM.

 FÜRS  -  Combined from FÜR DAS.

@{fg shine} PLURAL NOUNS@{fg text}

@{fg shine} The@{fg text}

 THE is always DIE when the Noun is Plural, regardless of wether the noun
 is Masculine, Feminine or Neuter. DIE plural becomes DEN after the word
 ON (AUF), IN (IN), UNDER (UNTER), etc.

      THE Plural: DIE (Nominative), DIE (Accusative), DEN (Dative)
                  and DER (Genitive).

 Plural Nouns are usually formed by adding E, N, S or ER to the end of the
 noun. Sometimes they add an Umlaut to the Main Vowel instead or aswell.
 Examples:

 The Man = Der Mann

 The Men = Die Männer    - Note the Umlaut (ä) on the main vowel A and the
                           ER, together with DIE, to form the Plural.


   The Lady = Die Dame

 The Ladies = Die DameN  - Note the N, together with DIE, to form the Plural


  Day = Tag

 Days = TagE


 Car = Auto

 Cars = AutoS


 If the plural comes after a Preposition like - With The Men - an N is
 added to the end:

 With The Men = Mit Den MännerN


 Most nouns and Masculine nouns that end in E form their plural by adding
 an N. Feminine nouns add N or EN, to form their plural. All other nouns
 add E, to form their plural. Some examples:

 Masculine:      Letter  = Brief        Day  = Tag          Boy  = Junge

                 Letters = BreifE       Days = TagE         Boys = JungeN

 Feminine:       Woman = Frau           Aunt  = Tante

                 Women = FrauEN         Aunts = TanteN


 There are some exceptions to the above. For example, Nouns that have `a',
 `o', `u' or `au' in their main vowel change `a' to ä, `o' to ö, `u' to ü
 and `au' to äu, aswell as adding an E (or ER - generally on Neuter nouns).
 Some examples:

 Masculine:      Son  = Sohn            Place  = Platz

                 Sons = SöhnE           Places = PlätzE

    Neuter:      House = Haus           Houses = HäusER

                 Book = Buch            Books  = BüchER


 If the Neuter or Masculine noun ends in EL, EN or ER they do not change
 their endings as above - They may still change their main vowel though.
 Some examples:

 Masculine:      Bird  = Vogel          Apple  =  Apfel

                 Birds = Vögel          Apples =  Äpfel

    Neuter:      Knife  = Messer

                 Knives = Messer


 Nouns of Foreign Origin and not ending in EL, EN or ER add EN.
 Some examples:

 Masculine:      Nephew  = Neffe        Soldier  = Soldat

                 Nephews = NeffEN       Soldiers = SoldatEN


@{fg shine} PERSONAL/MISCELLANEOUS PRONOUNS@{fg text}

  Nominative      Accusative         Dative               Genitive

    I   Ich        ME   Mich      To Me     Mir         MINE   Meiner

  YOU   Du        YOU   Dich      To You    Dir        YOURS   Deiner

   HE   Er        HIM   Ihn       To Him    Ihm          HIS   Seiner

  SHE   sie       HER   Sie       To Her    Ihr         HERS   Ihrer

   IT   Es         IT   Es        To It     Ihm          ITS   Seiner

   WE   Wir        US   Uns       To Us     Uns         OURS   Unser

  YOU   Ihr       YOU   Euch      To You    Euch       YOURS   Euer

 THEY   sie      THEM   Sie       To Them   Ihnen     THEIRS   Ihrer

  YOU   Sie       YOU   Sie       To You    Ihnen      YOURS   Ihrer


 Du is the familiar form of YOU and is used towards Relatives, Friends and
 Children.

@{fg shine} POSSESSIVE/MISCELLANEOUS ADJECTIVES@{fg text}

           Masculine & Neutral       Feminine & Plural


 MY              Mein                    Meine

 HIS / ITS       Sein                    Seine

 OUR             Unser                   Unsere

 YOUR            Ihr / Dein / Euer       Ihre / Deine / Euere

 THEIR / HER     ihr                     ihre


 NO, NOT A       Kein                    Keine (Nominative and Accusative)

                                         Keinen (Dative)

                                         Keiner (Genitive)


  MEIN - MEIN becomes MEINEM after the word ON (AUF), UNDER (UNTER), etc.

 MEINE - MEINE becomes MEINER after the word ON (AUF), UNDER (UNTER), etc.

 @{" Tenses " Link "Tenses"}
@endnode

@node Tenses "Tenses"

@{fg shine} TENSES@{fg text}

 Most Verbs end in the Infinitive (Dictionary Form) EN. The part before the
 EN is called the Stem (or Root) which never changes in the Regular Verb.
 Basically, you use the stem in order to get the Tense. Here are some
 examples (of the verb Wohn - To Live):


  Past or
  Imperfect: (Lived)           i lived  =  ich wohnTE

                       she/it/he lived  =  sie/es/er wohnTE

                              we lived  =  wir wohnTEN

         (singular/familiar) you lived  =  du wohnTEST

                    (plural) you lived  =  ihr wohnTET

             (polite/normal) you lived  =  sie wohnTEN

                            they lived  =  sie wohnTEN


 With past tense you basically look for GE at the front of the verb. This
 is a bit like ED in English past tense.



  Present (Living):             i live  =  ich wohnE

                       she/it/he lives  =  sie/es/er wohnT

                               we live  =  wir wohnEN

          (singular/familiar) you live  =  du wohnST

                     (plural) you live  =  ihr wohnT

              (polite/normal) you live  =  sie wohnEN

                             they live  =  sie wohnEN



  Future (To Live)         i will live  =  ich werde wohn

                   she/it/he will live  =  sie/es/er werde wohn

                          we will live  =  wir werde wohn

     (singular/familiar) you will live  =  du werde wohn

                (plural) you will live  =  ihr werde wohn

         (polite/normal) you will live  =  sie werde wohn

                        they will live  =  sie werde wohn


 Future tense normally uses the present tense.

 @{" Miscellaneous Information " Link "MiscInfo"}
@endnode

@node MiscInfo "Miscellaneous Information"

@{fg shine} MISCELLANEOUS INFORMATION@{fg text}

 * SIE - SIE can be interprretted as YOU, SHE or THEY. Sie, when meaning
         YOU, is written with a capital letter. Sie, when meaning THEY or
         SHE, is written with a small s. Please remember this as LGUI writes
         all words with a capital letter to indicate a new word.

 * DEM/DEN - If the previous Verb is NOT Active (the Object is not moving)
             then use DEM. But if the previous Verb is Active (the Object is
             moving) then use DEN.

 * Words ending in ICH, IG, ING and LING are normally Masculiine. The same
   goes for Days, Months, Seasons and Compass Directions.

 * Words ending in E, EI, HEIT and KEIT are normally Feminine.

 * Diminutive Nouns ending in CHEN or LEIN are normally Neutral.

 * Questions are formed by placing the Pronoun after the Verb. Examples:

         Er Spielt  =  He Is Playing

        Spielt Er?  =  Is He Playing?

      Sie Sind ...  =  You Are ...

     Sind Sie ...?  =  Are You ...?

       Es Gibt ...  =  There Is ...

      Gibt Es ...?  =  Is There ...?

 * Negatives are usually formed by putting NICHT at the end of your
   sentence. Example:

     Er Spielt Nicht = He Is Not Playing

 * HIN and HER words. HIN implies motion away from (you) the speaker and HER
   implies motion towards (you) the speaker.

 * ß is SS. SS is used between two Vowels and when a first vowel is short
   (i.e. ü - Müssen). ß is used in all other uses - After a long Vowel
   (i.e. Au - Draußen), At the end of a word (i.e. Daß, Weiß, Grüß, etc),
   Before T (i.e. Heißt), etc.

 * Gehen is only used for walking. Fahren (Fahr words) is used for transport
   So in travelling sentences I have used a country name, city name or a
   have-to-drive-to-place to clarify between Gehen and Fahren (i.e. I am
   going to Germany - Ich fahre nach Deutschland. I am going to the theatre
   - Ich fahre zum theater). For Gehen I have used words like Market (i.e. I
   am going to the Market - Ich gehe in der Markt).

 * Some german words are made up of two words - The infinitive is one.

   The verb is often split when used in a sentence. Aufstehen (to get up) is
   made from Auf (up) and Stehen (to stand). You use Stehen like a normal
   verb but Auf usually goes to the end of the sentence. Example:

     TOM gets up at eight o'clock - TOM steht um acht uhr auf

 @{" Pronunciation " Link "Pronunciation"}
@endnode

@node Pronunciation "Pronunciation"

@{fg shine} PRONUNCIATION@{fg text}

  Long a  -  sound: Ah.

 Short a  -  sound: Uh.

       ä  -  sound: Ai (as in: Air) or Eh (as in: Bed).

      au  -  sound: How.

      äu  -  sound: Oy.

      ch  -  sound: k (like a small a in school - ka).

     chs  -  sound: x/ks (as in: Six).

  Long e  -  sound: Ay.

 Short e  -  sound: Eh.

      ei  -  sound: I/Eye (as in: Fine).

      er  -  sound: Er or Air (depending on the word).

      eu  -  sound: Oy.

       i  -  sound: Ih (as in: Bit) or Ee (as in: Weed).

      ie  -  sound: Ee (as in: Meet).

       j  -  sound: Y (e.g: Ja = Yah).

      kn  -  K and N are pronounced as seperate words. e.g: knie = K Nee

  Long o  -  sound: Oe.

 Short o  -  sound: Oh.

       o  -  sound: O (as in: Order).

       ö  -  sound: Er (as in: First).

      qu  -  Q and U are pronounced as seperate words. Q sound: K.
             e.g: Qualität = K Vulit Ayt

       s  -  sound: Z (as in: Zoo), before a vowel.

       s  -  sound: S/Ss (as in: Sale), at the end of a word.

       s  -  sound: Sh, before P. e.g: Spiel = Shpeel.

     sch  -  sound: Sh (as in: Sheep).

    ss/ß  -  sound: ss, the same as pronounced in English.

      th  - sound: T (as in: Tent).

      tz  - sound: Ts (e.g: Netz = Nets).

       u  -  sound: Uh/Oo (as in: Good) or Who/Oo (as in: Mood).

       ü  -  sound: Ui.

       v  -  sound: F (as in: Foot) or V (as in: Vase).

       w  -  sound: usually V (as in: Vase).

       x  -  sound: X/Cks (as in: Wax).

       z  -  sound: Ts (as in: Bits).


 A final E is pronounced as ER.

 A final D is pronounced as T (e.g: Abend is Ah (Long a) Bent (d becomes t).

 @{" Speech " Link "Speech"}
@endnode

@node Speech "Speech"

@{fg shine} SPEECH@{fg text}

 Overall, I would suggest you use the Speech File/s to get to know how a
 word is spoken (via each Syllable) as opposed to using the Speech File/s as
 the perfect way to say/pronounce a word. Thus, I would recommend (to some
 degree) that you try to imitate a German's Voice.
@{fg fill}
 To a certain degree any language created on a computer is going to have its
 faults until you actually start reading/speaking that language. Which by
 then people should be correcting you anyway. Thus, treat any language (not
 just those created on a computer) as the guidelines to that language and
 not as a 100% perfect language, simply because Books have writing mistakes
 in them just the same as computers have speech faults, etc. So if you spot
 a mistake in a sentence or mispronunciation in a speech file, try and
 correct it if you can. Thus, you will have piece of mind that your copy of
 a language file is closer to near perfect.

 Many pronunciations are very close to their Human Sound. However, due to
 Amiga Pronunciation, a small percentage of incorrect pronunciation on a
 word/syllable may make that word as a whole sound slightly incorrect. This
 is bound to happen simply because the Amiga, and I, are not perfect.
 However, take note of the above said and you should find that once you have
 a Foreign friend to help you with words and pronunciation the Amiga Speech
 isn't as bad as some people make it out to be.

 Even if a language was to be created at 100% perfect you are still adviced
 to have a Dictionary lying around simply because you may still need to look
 up words for their meaning, etc of course.@{fg text}

 @{" Dictionary " Link "Dictionary"}
@endnode

@node Dictionary "Dictionary"

@{fg shine} DICTIONARY@{fg text}

 This section is just to clarify what each item (Noun, Adjective, etc) is
 when it is German - An item may/may not follow the same rule/s as in
 English Grammar, for example.

@{fg shine} Nouns@{fg text}

 Nouns are words used for names of Things, Ideas and Living Creatures
 (including Humans and Animals). All nouns begin with a capital letter.

@{fg shine} Pronouns@{fg text}

 A Personal Pronoun (He, Yours, Me, etc) is a word used in place of a Noun.
 For example. If you said "The cat ate your food". Your second sentence
 might use one or more pronouns like so "He ate yours aswell". HE was used
 instead of THE CAT and YOURS was used instead of FOOD. In other words. You
 did not have to say "The cat ate your food aswell". You used pronouns to
 cut the sentence down.

@{fg shine} Prepositions@{fg text}

 Prepositions are small words that are used to link other words in a
 sentence. They normally precede Nouns or Pronouns and indicate Where, How
 or When something is happening. Examples:

 Where - she is IN town, she is IN THE bathroom, she is AT THE door

   How - she is frying WITH oil, she is moping WITH THE mop, she is
         cooking WITH A saucepan

  When - she is asleep AT 7 O'Clock, she is awake UNTIL midnight

@{fg shine} Adjectives@{fg text}

 An Adjective describes something, usually a Noun. For example, the
 adjective BROWN can be used to described a Noun like TREE - the BROWN tree.
 The same goes with the adjective BIG - the BIG tree.

 When an Adjective is used before a Noun (i.e. A Small Man - the Noun = Man
 and the Adjective = Small) it must agree with that noun in 3 ways:

 1 In number (Singular or Plural)

 2 In Gender (Masculine, Feminine or Neuter)

 3 In Case (Nomative, Accusative, Genitive or Dative)

 When an Adjective is used after a Verb (i.e. She Is Slim - the Verb = Is
 and the Adjective = Slim) it follows the same rules as in English.

 After THE (Die, etc) adjectives add E in the singular and EN in the plural.
 After A (eine, etc) adjectives add ER in the masculine, E in the feminine
 and ES in the neuter.

@{fg shine} Verbs@{fg text}

 A Verb is an Action word. Where an adjective describes something with a
 word a verb describes or does something with action. For example. If I
 describe a tree I use an adjective - the BIG tree. But sometimes this is
 not possible. For example. If I describe "He ran in a funny walk like this"
 I cannot show you that funny walk with a description (an adjective).
 I would have to show you with Action (I.e. I would have to do a funny walk,
 in order to describe the funny walk). This is exactly the job of a verb. To
 describe or do something with action words (I.e. RUN to the shop, THINK,
 EAT the food, etc).

 Verbs can change depending on who is doing the action. For example "I Make"
 but "He Makes". And they have different tenses according to when the action
 takes place. For example "i MAKE breakfast" (Future Tense) whereas
 "he MADE breakfast" (Past Tense).

 Verbs generally tell us: What is happening, Who or What is doing the action
 and Time (i.e. Past/Present/Future). A Verb will usually have a Subject
 (i.e. I, We, She, etc) which tells you who or what is doing the action.

 The Infinite form of a verb is its basic form (I.e. To Make, To Run, etc).
 A Dictionary normally lists words in their Infinite form.

 In german sentences the verb always goes in second place. The subject of
 the sentence usually goes first (i.e. Er geht zu bett - He goes to bett),
 but if Time comes first for example the verb stays where it is and the
 subject of the sentence goes after it (i.e. Um neun uhr geht er zu bett -
 At nine o'clock he goes to bed / He goes to bed at nine o'clock).

@{fg shine} Adverbs@{fg text}

 An Adverb is a word that gives more information about an action. Many
 adverbs describe how a verb's action is done. For example "Slowly", as in
 "He opens the door slowly". Other adverbs say when an action happens. For
 example "Yesterday". Or where an action happens. For example "Here".

@{fg shine} Subject or Object?@{fg text}

 A Noun or Pronoun is the Subject when it is doing the action. For example.
 "THE DOG barks" or "HE shouts" - THE DOG (and HE) is the subject.

 A Noun or Pronoun is the Direct Object when the action is done to it. For
 example. "he strokes THE DOG" or "he strokes HIM" - THE DOG (and HIM) is
 the direct object.

 A Noun or Pronoun can also be an Indirect Object. For example.
 "he gives THE DOG a bone" - THE DOG is the indirect object and A BONE is
 the direct object. You can normally tell an indirect object because it
 could have a preposition (TO, AT, FROM, etc) in front of it. Therefore. In
 the above you could say "he gives a bone TO THE DOG". With a pronoun
 "give HIM the bone" you could say "give the bone TO HIM".

 Depending on whether a Noun or Pronoun is the Subject, Direct Object or
 Indirect Object decides what Case it should go in (Dative, Accusative, etc)
 Read a good German book/dictionary for more information.
@endnode

